–1408":"1372–1408","1312–1345":"1312–1345","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1374":"1374","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1410":"1410","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1408":"1408","about 1362":"circa 1362","about 1373":"circa 1373","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Honiton, Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hounton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1342–1374":"1342–1374","1342–1375":"1342–1375","1362–1410":"1362–1410","1372–1408":"1372–1408","1312–1345":"1312–1345","1326–1379":"1326–1379","1374":"1374","1362":"1362","1372":"1372","1326":"1326","1379":"1379","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1410":"1410","1342":"1342","1375":"1375","1408":"1408","about 1362":"about 1362","about 1373":"about 1373","Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Scrivelsby, Lincolnshire, England","Honiton, Devonshire, England":"Honiton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Hounton, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Enland, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Tremenent was born in 1342, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard Tremenent, was 30 and her mother, Margaret Donnett, was 16. She married Walter Dymock or Dymoke about 1373, in Devon, England. They